Introduction

https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/motor-vehicle-collisions-crashes

For this project, I analyzed the above data set, which consisted of record of motor vehicle crashes from 2012 to February 2025 in New York City. The data set records each motor vehicle incident as well as the time, location, vehicles involved, and reasons for the crash. My motivation for this data set was that I had hoped to analyze which specific model of car was responsible for car crashes, but the data was too messy to do so. I also dislike Honda Civics and Nissan Altimas and hoped to statistically prove my vendetta against them. Aside from my personal beliefs, I did think that this data was interesting and would maybe provide myself some interesting insights into traffic data.

To start, this data set was extremely messy and I needed clean up many of the categorical values. Using ChatGPT, I classified the Vehicle columns and contributing factor columns into a smaller set of categories that would be easier to analyze.

Transform Vehicle Column

normalize_text <- function(text) {
  text <- tolower(text)  
  text <- gsub("[^a-z0-9\\s-]", "", text)  
  trimws(text)  
}

# Define classification categories
vehicle_map <- list(
  "passenger" = c("car", "suv", "convertible", "coupe", "sedan", "minivan", "van", "pickup","stationwagonsportutilityvehicle"),
  "public_transport" = c("bus", "school bus", "transit", "livery", "shuttle"),
  "two_wheeled" = c("motorcycle", "moped", "scooter", "bicycle", "bike", "e-bike", "e-scooter"),
  "emergency" = c("ambulance", "fire truck", "fire engine", "police", "fdny", "ems", "rescue"),
  "commercial_delivery" = c("truck", "box truck", "pickup truck", "cargo", "delivery", "freight", "semi", "big rig"),
  "construction_heavy" = c("bulldozer", "excavator", "crane", "cement mixer", "forklift", "dump truck", "tractor"),
  "government_utility" = c("sanitation", "postal", "utility", "fdny", "nypd", "gov", "city vehicle"),
  "specialty" = c("golf cart", "limo", "armored truck", "horse carriage", "hearse", "snowplow", "street sweeper"),
  "N/A" = c("")
)

map_vehicle <- function(vehicle) {
  for (category in names(vehicle_map)) {
    if (vehicle %in% vehicle_map[[category]]) {
      return(category)
    }
  }
  return("Other")  # Default category if no match is found
}
motor_crashes$normalized_vehicles_1 = normalize_text(motor_crashes$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1)
motor_crashes$normalized_vehicles_2 = normalize_text(motor_crashes$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.2)

motor_crashes = motor_crashes %>% mutate(vehicle_class_1 = sapply(normalized_vehicles_1,map_vehicle),
                                         vehicle_class_2 = sapply(normalized_vehicles_2,map_vehicle))

I repeated the same process for the contributing factors.

Transform Contributing Factors

category_mapping <- list(
  "Substance Impairment" = c("Alcohol Involvement", "Drugs (illegal)", "Prescription Medication"),
  "Reckless Driving" = c("Aggressive Driving/Road Rage", "Following Too Closely", "Unsafe Speed", 
                         "Unsafe Lane Changing", "Passing Too Closely", "Passing or Lane Usage Improper"),
  "Driver Distraction" = c("Driver Inattention/Distraction", "Cell Phone (hand-held)", "Cell Phone (hands-free)", 
                           "Texting", "Using On Board Navigation Device", "Other Electronic Device", 
                           "Eating or Drinking", "Passenger Distraction", "Outside Car Distraction"),
  "Driver Error" = c("Driver Inexperience", "Reaction to Other Uninvolved Vehicle", "Reaction to Uninvolved Vehicle"),
  "Fatigue" = c("Fatigued/Drowsy", "Fell Asleep"),
  "Medical Conditions" = c("Lost Consciousness", "Illness", "Physical Disability"),
  "Vehicle Defects" = c("Accelerator Defective", "Brakes Defective", "Steering Failure", "Headlights Defective", 
                        "Other Lighting Defects", "Tinted Windows", "Tire Failure/Inadequate", "Tow Hitch Defective"),
  "Roadway Defects" = c("Lane Marking Improper/Inadequate", "Pavement Defective", "Shoulders Defective/Improper", 
                        "Traffic Control Device Improper/Non-Working"),
  "Environmental Factors" = c("Animals Action", "Obstruction/Debris", "Glare", "View Obstructed/Limited", 
                              "Windshield Inadequate", "Pedestrian/Bicyclist/Other Pedestrian Error/Confusion"),
  "N/A" = c(""),
  "Other" = c()  # Placeholder for any uncategorized reasons
)
map_category <- function(reason) {
  for (category in names(category_mapping)) {
    if (reason %in% category_mapping[[category]]) {
      return(category)
    }
  }
  return("Other")  # Default category if no match is found
}

motor_crashes = motor_crashes %>% mutate(factor1 = sapply(CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1,map_category),
                                     factor2 = sapply(CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.2,map_category)
                                     )

In addition to the vehicle classes and the contributing factors, I also wanted to modify the recorded times into a numerical variable that I could plot. The following code snippet shows what I did to convert the original date strings into numerical values and POSIXlt.

Fix Times

full_date = paste(motor_crashes$CRASH.DATE,motor_crashes$CRASH.TIME)
motor_crashes$corrected_datetime = strptime(full_date, "%m/%d/%Y %H:%M")
motor_crashes = motor_crashes %>% mutate(year = as.integer(format(corrected_datetime,"%Y")),
                                         hour = corrected_datetime$hour,
                                         minute = corrected_datetime$min,
                                         time_hrs = hour + minute/60)

I decided to add some extra binary variables to add some extra level of complexity or areas of analysis that I thought would be good to take a look at as well. Unfortunately, I did not get the chance to analyze the data using all of these extra variables.

Add Extra Variables

motor_crashes = motor_crashes %>% mutate(hasDeath = NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.KILLED > 0,
                                         hasInjury = NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.INJURED > 0,
                                         multiVehicleCrash = VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1 != "" & VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.2 != "" & VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.3 != "" | VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.4 != "" | VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.5 != "")

Obviously on a set of regular axes, the latitude and longitude would not provide any real value. However, I did recall that in a previous visualization assignment, I saw that it was possible to plot coordinates on a geographic map. At first, I plotted the entire data set on the same map and it produced a giant blob of data points. To create a better looking plot of the data points, I filtered the data points to show motor crashes in New York City in January 2025.

Next, I wanted to examine the distribution between the total number of crashes per hour of the day in the data set. I plotted the numerical value of hour, which range from 0 to 24, with the count of data points that fall under each hour. I produced the following plot and added some color to show which factors were most prevalent during each hour of the day.

Histogram of Crash Times

filter(motor_crashes, factor1 != "Other" & factor1 != "N/A") %>% 
  mutate(hour = corrected_datetime$hour,
         minute = corrected_datetime$min) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = hour + minute / 60, color = factor1)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1) +
  labs(title = "Histogram of Crash Times", x = "Hour of the Day", y = "Count")

Looking at this histogram, we see that the most car crashes occur during the 5 PM rush hour. This makes sense as many people are impatient trying to get home and rush through traffic. Another interesting point we can take from this histogram is that distracted driving and reckless driving are the most common factors that people get into a car crash for. Using this observation from the previous histogram, I took a closer look at the distribution of distracted driving accidents.

Histogram of Distracted Driving Accidents

filter(motor_crashes,factor1 == "Driver Distraction" & vehicle_class_1 != "N/A" & vehicle_class_1 != "Other") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, color = vehicle_class_1)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1) +
  labs(title = "Number of Distracted Driving Accidents per Year", x = "Year", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

Looking at this histogram, which is colored by vehicle, we see that passenger cars are the common vehicle that are involved in distracted driving incidents. This makes sense since passenger vehicle make up a pretty large portion of the entire data set. From the previous visualizations, we can conclude that passenger vehicles are the most common vehicles involved in distracted driving accidents and that distracted and reckless driving are the most frequent reasons for motor accidents.

Statistical Analysis and Linear Regression

Since this data set mainly consisted of categorical variables, I decided to look at the correlation between the number of people injured vs. the time of day. My thought process into this linear regression was that based off of the visualizations from the previous section. I predicted that there must be some connection that more people get injured as the day progresses. Surprisingly, not every entry in the data set contains an injury nor a death. I proceeded with the linear regression by filtering out entries without an injury and also examined the correlation coefficients. For all analyses, I set alpha = 0.05 to determine significance.

motor_injuries = motor_crashes %>% filter(hasInjury)
motor_injuries %>% ggplot(aes(x=time_hrs,y=NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.INJURED)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = 'lm') + labs(x="Time (24hrs)", y="Number of People Injured", title = "Number of People Injured vs. Time of Day")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

summary(lm(formula = NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.INJURED ~ time_hrs, data = motor_injuries))

From the scatter plot, we see that the linear regression line looks very close to a constant line. Looking at the linear regression output, the coefficient of time is close to 0, which suggests that there is no correlation between the time and number of people injured. To further investigate this, I calculated the Pearson and Spearman correlation coefficients to get another metric of the correlation. Both outputs show that there is no linear correlation between between the time and number of people injured. It was also interesting to see that the Pearson test returned a significant p-value and Spearman returned an insignificant p-value. Lastly, I conducted a t-test to see if there was a difference in average time of accidents between accidents with and without a death.

t.test(data = motor_crashes, time_hrs ~ hasDeath)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  time_hrs by hasDeath
## t = 3.0156, df = 1850.3, p-value = 0.0026
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group FALSE and group TRUE is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1684531 0.7951659
## sample estimates:
## mean in group FALSE  mean in group TRUE 
##            13.67243            13.19062

Shockingly enough, the t-test showed that there was a statistical significant difference in the average times between accidents with and without a death. The confidence interval given from the output also shows that the true difference in times are within under 1 hour of each other. Looking at the average time of crash between the 2 groups, we see that the average times are similar but significantly different from each other.

Conclusions

From the visualizations of the data, we see that distracted driving and reckless driving are 2 of the main contributing factors that cause motor vehicle accidents. We also see that passenger vehicles are the common culprit in distract driving accidents, which makes sense since most of the data set is comprised of passenger vehicle accidents. From our statistical analyses, we found that there was no significant correlation between the time of day and the number of people injured in a crash. However, we did find that there is a significant difference in the average time of a crash and whether or not someone died in that crash.
